Introduction

Kenneth did RNAseq on lung primary cells.

That data was aligned by the genome center, we have the preliminary reports:

  • qc_report_genome_center.html : quality control of the alignment of the data

  • initial_report_genome_center: describes each sample (used for annotations) and did a basic PCA + how many genes are differentially expressed when comparing conditions.

We want to know what pathways/processes changed after different treatments. We are specifically interested in seeing why cytokines (IL5, IL13, ILxx) induce SPREADS but do not when coupled with pitavastatin.

So ultimately, what is pitavastatin suppressing?

What is in common and what is specific to each conditions?

Venn diagram

Compare all the differentially expressed genes vs control to each other. This plot allows us to know which genes can be found to be perturbed vs control in all conditions as well as those that are specific to one condition or another.

UP in cytokine and DOWN in Cyt + Pit

Now let’s look at the 1878 + 1402 (3280) genes that are common to cytokines and cyto+statin treatments and the 666 + 163 (829) genes that look to have changed in cytokines vs ctrl. The hope is to find some that are up in cytokine and down or unchanged in statin+cyto vs ctrl. There are 11 (up and down) + 366 (up and unchanged) such genes.

Genes of interest

Based on our growing hypothesis from scanning the previous results, I checked the recent literature about other known or emergent roles of these proteins, which would not appear in an ORA search because the dataset takes some time to be updated. I checked for links to ERK/EGFR signaling and TNFa production. Interstingly, most of the proteins that had a log2Fc > 1 in cytokine and were specifically only changing in cytokines and not the double treatment seem to fit our expectations.

  • TSPAN8: “We, therefore propose that Tspan8 contributes to tumorigenesis through enhanced ADAM17-mediated TNF α release”

  • HSPA1A: “Exogenous heat shock proteins HSPA1A and HSPB1 regulate TNF-α, IL-1β and IL-10 secretion from monocytic cells”

  • HSP1B: see above

  • EPHA3: “We examined ERK1/2 phosphorylation in both WK1 and U251 cells and found that the ERK/MAPK pathway was more highly activated in EphA3 KD cells” “EPHA3 is upregulated by EGF in glioblastoma cells”

  • SMOC2: “TGF-β1/SMOC2/AKT and ERK axis regulates proliferation, migration, and fibroblast to myofibroblast transformation in lung fibroblast, contributing with the asthma progression”

  • IL12RB2: “IL12 and TNFa are two major inflammation mediators in mammals” “IL-12-dependent activation of ERK1/2 in human T lymphoblasts”

  • DOK1: “LPLI inhibits ERK phosphorylation through DOK1”

  • HCK: “Hck tyrosine kinase activity modulates tumor necrosis factor production by murine macrophages”

  • EGR2: “Novel pro-survival functions of the Kruppel-like transcription factor Egr2 in promotion of macrophage colony-stimulating factor-mediated osteoclast survival downstream of the MEK/ERK pathway” + “NFκB and MAPK signalling pathways mediate TNFα-induced Early Growth Response gene transcription leading to aromatase expression”

  • GPER1: “Treatment GPER1-specific agonist lead to sustained and transient activity of EGF/ERK and EGFR/AKT pathways in [2] HCC cell lines” + “GPER negatively regulates TNFα-induced IL-6 production”

Other genes of interest, had the highest logFc in cytokine and were unchanged in pitcyt

  • SHISA8: Predicted to be part of AMPA glutamate receptor complex

  • LRRTM2: Regulates surface expression of AMPA receptors and instructs the development of functional glutamate release sites.

-> TNFa induces trafficking of AMPA to mb in CNS neurons

All in all our gene of interest point in

  • OXPHOS-involved proteins are very up in cytokines vs double treatment
  • TNFa release/production is up
